<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>/</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Written evidence from the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Chartered Institution of Highways and Transportation (CIHT) (SRN 035)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">CIHT is a membership organisation representing over 12,000 people who work in the highways and transportation sector.  CIHT members plan, design, build, operate and maintain best-in-class transport systems </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">and infrastructure, whilst respecting the imperatives of improving safety, ensuring economic competitiveness and minimising environmental impact.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">CIHT welcomes the opportunity to submit evidence to the Transport</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Select Committee</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">’</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> consultation on </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the Stra</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">tegic Road network</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">This response incorporates the views of CIHT’s Council which </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">is a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">represent</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ative body of our members</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">’</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> interests and opinions</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. We would welcome the opportunity to expand upon our response as required.</span></p><h1 style="font-weight:normal; margin:12pt 0pt 0pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid"><span style="color:#2e74b5; font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:16pt">Summary</span><a name="_GoBack"></a></h1><h3 style="font-weight:normal; margin:2pt 0pt 0pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid"><span style="color:#1f4d78; font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:12pt">Action for R</span><span style="color:#1f4d78; font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:12pt">oads </span><span style="color:#1f4d78; font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:12pt">welcome</span></h3><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">CI</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">HT welcomes the recognition of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the importance of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">certainty of investment an</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">d reform to the Highways Agency set out in Action for Roads. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">More radical changes to the management of the network may have the capacity for greater improvements in the longer ter</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">m </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">and it is encouraging</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> that such options have been considered in Action for Roads.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The standard of highway expertise in the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">United Kingdom</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> is very high and is recognised worldwide. Our networks are amongst the safest in the world and our professional stan</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">dards are highly regarded. The </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">United Kingdom</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> has contributed significantly to the development of highways as an increasingly more efficient sector of industry.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">It is therefore appropriate that Action for Roads proposes an incremental change to the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">management of the Strategic road network that builds on that expertise. Nevertheless the changes that are required do require </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">a boldness</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> in approach so that the investment proposed can be used effectively to deliver real improvements to customers over time</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><h3 style="font-weight:normal; margin:2pt 0pt 0pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid"><span style="color:#1f4d78; font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:12pt">S</span><span style="color:#1f4d78; font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:12pt">ector needs </span><span style="color:#1f4d78; font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:12pt">certainty</span></h3><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Certainty</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and continuity</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> of investment over a sustained period is important if overall improvements to the network are to be delivered effectively and efficiently. This need for certainty applies both to the reformed Highways Ag</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ency and other “client” bodies and the wider supply chain of organisations working in the sector.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Government needs to provide the certainty required by the supply chain side of the sector to invest in resource and capability to deliver the investment envi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">saged. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The Roads Investment Strategy needs to be confirmed and be committed to quickly by all parties. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">This will allow the Highways Agency to develop a robust pipeline of requirements for its supply chain in a form that allows the supply chain to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">innovate and invest over a period of time.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><h3 style="font-weight:normal; margin:2pt 0pt 0pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid"><span style="color:#1f4d78; font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:12pt">Clear strategy required</span></h3><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">CIHT </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">argues</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> that there is a clear need for a tra</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">nsportation strategy that sets a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">clear framework of requirements over a sustained period fo</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">r all elements of our transportation </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">networks. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">This strategy (or strategies) should include the strategic and local road networks,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> r</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ail, aviation and ports and set</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> out how those networks integrate with one another.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The publication of Action for Roads is welcome in that it </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">sets out the importance of t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">he strategic road network and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">aims to define the needs of the strategic road network, linking investment over a period to the management structure required to deliver it. There is a concern that the absence of a national transport strategy (or strategies) </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">may mean that the investment identified in Action for Roads is not utilised effectively. The strategy should cove</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">r</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> other transport modes and importantly the overarching policy for the local roads network.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In developing its approach the government needs t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">o ensure that the importance of understanding how customer needs are addressed in the new model for operation and be specific about how those needs are developed, protected and monitored by a regulator or other arrangement.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><h3 style="font-weight:normal; margin:2pt 0pt 0pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid"><span style="color:#1f4d78; font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:12pt">R</span><span style="color:#1f4d78; font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:12pt">ecognition of the degree of </span><span style="color:#1f4d78; font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:12pt">ch</span><span style="color:#1f4d78; font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:12pt">ange</span><span style="color:#1f4d78; font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="color:#1f4d78; font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:12pt">required</span></h3><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The government needs to be bold in recognising the capabilities required of a reformed Highways Agency. Those capabilities are likely to include a clearer appreciation of customer requirements and an expanded commercial capability, informed </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">by other sectors. There is also a need for the reformed organisation to have more freedom to allow more innovation and more agility in decision making.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><h3 style="font-weight:normal; margin:2pt 0pt 0pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid"><span style="color:#1f4d78; font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:12pt">Local roads are a key part of the network</span></h3><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Government should recognise that the success of an improved </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">strategic network in meeting customer needs cannot be met without the local road network being also considered as part of a holistic solution that customers require.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The Department for Transport and government need to clearly define the role of the transp</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ortation network in delivering the policies of the government. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Action for Roads envisages the publication of a draft national policy statement on national networks in 2013. This needs to clearly set out the relationship of the strategic network to other </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">networks, including the local highway network. It also needs to demonstrate how the policy links to both national and local planning policy, setting out a clear framework for the responsibility and accountability of developing the network.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">response to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the questions are</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> set out on the following pages.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 72pt 0pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><h1 style="font-weight:normal; margin:12pt 0pt 0pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid"><span style="color:#2e74b5; font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:16pt">&#xa0;</span></h1><h1 style="font-weight:normal; margin:12pt 0pt 0pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid"><span style="color:#2e74b5; font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:16pt">Response to questions</span></h1><h1 style="font-weight:normal; margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="color:#2e74b5; font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:16pt">1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="color:#2e74b5; font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:16pt">How will the policies set out in the Government’s “Action for Roads” command paper improve the strategic road network for all road users, whilst also improving the environment?</span></h1><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">1.1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">CIHT welcomes the recognition of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the importance of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">certainty of investment and reform to the Highways Agency.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">1.2.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The current proposals to be enacted in legislation within this Parliamentary cycle offer a pragmatic and deliverable approach to change.  More </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">radical changes</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, for example the introduction of a Regulated Utility Model in conjunction with direct user charging,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> to the management of the network may have the capacity for greater improvements in the longer term and it is good that such options have be</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">en considered in Action for Roads.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">1.3.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Certainty of investment over a sustained period is important if overall improvements to the network are to be delivered effectively and efficiently. This need for certainty applies both to the reformed Highways Agency and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> other “client” bodies and the wider supply chain of organisations working in the sector. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">1.4.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The five year funding period set out (in the Road Investment Strategy) is a welcome improvement from annualised budget cycles.  However, this falls short of the peri</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ods required to undertake a holistic approach to asset management and delivery of customer expectations.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">1.5.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Experience from other models and schemes, for example on the M25 D</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">esign Build Finance &amp; Operate</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> scheme, and PFI investments in the local highway sect</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">or have delivered real benefits through considering needs over a 25 year period.  Such approaches have enabled ambitious investment programmes to be delivered over a five year period followed by managed, longer operational periods. This 'invest to save' ap</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">proach helps reduce ongoing operational costs through upfront investment in the asset. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">1.6.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Certainty of investment over a sustained period will also allow a more resilient network to be developed, allowing the reformed Highways Agency and its supply chain to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">meet the potential challenges of climate change by taking a longer term view of the needs of the network.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">1.7.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The increased level of investment is also welcomed as the sector has faced budget reductions that have led to asset deterioration.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> The investment ide</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ntified will enable a series of key benefits to be delivered such as improving capacity, reducing congestion and improving reliability. These benefits will improve the network for users and deliver environmental benefits</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">..</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">1.8.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The sector already has a lot of e</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">xperience to build on.  For instance, the lessons learnt from the managed motorways programme already underway have demonstrated the ability of the sector to deliver additional capacity withi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">n existing highway corridors. These improvements have been delive</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">red more efficiently than full motorway improvements, delivering benefits to users and the environment in a shorter timescale.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">1.9.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Future Investment strategies should be informed by linking an understanding of the assets required to deliver all the purposes of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the network derived from customer need. A proposed approach is set out in our response to Question 3 below.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">1.10.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Certainty of investment and clarity of the pipeline of works anticipated is fundamental to the ability of the supply chain to deliver a significant</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> programme of investment in the timescales set out. If certainty is not delivered then </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">providing </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">increased resource will have a time lag before benefits can be </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">fully </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">delivered.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">1.11.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">It is welcome that the importance of the local road network is recognised by Ac</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">tion for Roads and that the effects on non-vehicular highway users are addressed to some degree. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">1.12.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Nearly all journeys on the strategic road network begin and end on the local highway network. Unless linked to consideration of wider effects, improvements to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the strategic road network (SRN) may have significant effects upon the local road network affecting all highway users, local communities and the environment. These effects may occur through diversion onto unsuitable parts of the network by charging, conge</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">stion or control of access to the SRN. Customers do not take a different view of the networks they travel </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">on,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> a consistent appropriate standard of service delivery needs to be the aim.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">1.13.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The issue of how the viewpoint of customers is taken into account in th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e development of the network is fundamental to real and lasting improvements in the network. The role of a “regulator” acting in customers interests is commonplace in other sectors and in the transport sector and should be introduced alongside changes to t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">he form of the Highways Agency in the way it manages the network. We set out in our response to Question 3 below how the requirements of customers should be </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">developed,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> a regulator could play an important role in that.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">1.14.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Consideration of the local road networ</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">k in conjunction with highway authorities, Local Transport Boards (LTBs) and Local Enterprise Partnerships (LEPs) is vital and needs to be recognised and implemented as part of the changes proposed set out in Action for Roads.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">1.15.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The increased amount of maint</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">enance investment for the local road network is welcome.  However, this must be considered alongside a reduced revenue budget for local authorities. There is the risk that the overall increase in investment could be jeopardised if the issue of the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">contribu</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">tion</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> that the local network makes to the success of the S</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">RN</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> is not fully considered.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">1.16.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">CIHT welcomes and supports the importance of the Highways Maintenance Efficiency Programme (HMEP) </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">http://www.dft.gov.uk/hmep</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> in delivering change to the local roads sector</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and will continue to work with the programme to ensure that linkages to the development of the SRN are maintained and enhanced.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><h1 style="font-weight:normal; margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="color:#2e74b5; font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:16pt">2.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="color:#2e74b5; font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:16pt">How does the Government’s policy for roads link with planning for other transport modes?</span></h1><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">2.1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">CIHT </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">argues</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> that there is a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">real</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> need for a tra</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">nsportation strategy that sets a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">clear framework of requirements over a sustained period fo</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">r all elements of our transportation networks. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">This strategy (or strategies) should include the strategic and local road networks,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> r</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ail, aviation and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> ports and set</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> out how those networks integrate with one another.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">2.2.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The publication of Action for Roads is welcome in that it </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">sets out the importance of the SRN and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">aims to define the needs of the network, linking investment over a period to the management structure required to deliver it. There is a concern that the absence of a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">N</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ational </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ransport </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">S</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">trategy (or strategies) may mean that the investment identified in Ac</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">tion for Roads is not utilised effectively. The strategy should cove</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">r</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> other transport modes and importantly the overarching policy for the local roads network.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">2.3.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">It is welcome that the government have, over time, devolved responsibility for the local roads n</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">etwork to a local level in terms of decisions where funding should be spent</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">however</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> an overall policy framework is required for highway authorities and other bodies to work within. T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">h</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">is must set out the aims and objectives of the network in relation to th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e needs of the country. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">2.4.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">There could be benefit in considering the reform of how improvements to the local road network are delivered. The current arrangement contains inefficiencies, introduces inconsistencies and does not make best use of the pool of ski</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">lled resource available.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">2.5.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">How the national and local highway network contributes to and enables planning policy to be developed effectively and sustainably across the country is a clear requirement of government at all levels</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">2.6.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">A clear understanding of the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">purposes of the highway network for all its customers will help develop that strategy and its development will also allow clear accountability for delivery of the strategy to be set out to the different bodies required to deliver it.</span></p><h1 style="font-weight:normal; margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="color:#2e74b5; font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:16pt">3.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="color:#2e74b5; font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:16pt">How reliable is the Go</span><span style="color:#2e74b5; font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:16pt">vernment’s forecast for growth in demand for the strategic road network? How should the Government deal with uncertainty in its forecast?</span></h1><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">3.1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The contribution that the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">highway</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> netw</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ork is required to make to a range of policy areas should </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">be clearly defined in</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the strategy described above</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> in our response to Question 2</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. In order to develop a robust prediction to underpin development of the network a series of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">key steps should be undertaken a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">longside existing economic modelling tools</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">3.2.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The development of these st</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">eps should be undertaken by all engaged in the sector including</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the gove</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">rnment, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Highways Agency and related authorities on the adjoining networks</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, groups representing the sector and the supply chain to the sector. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">3.3.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The steps CIHT propose, based on a system</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s thinking approach, are:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 61.2pt; text-indent:-25.2pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">3.3.1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Identify the different classes of groups</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> (customers)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> who are reliant on the network. As well as </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">different </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">users of the network these customer groups could in</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">clude amongst others, adjacent communities, non-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">users of the network, th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e environment, her</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">itage and the highway asset itself.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 61.2pt; text-indent:-25.2pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">3.3.2.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Identify </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the different purposes that the network is required to deli</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ver to different customer groups</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 61.2pt; text-indent:-25.2pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">3.3.3.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Analysis to confirm how the network will best meet the different purposes identified and to identify </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">what investment is required to meet those different purposes of all customers.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 61.2pt; text-indent:-25.2pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">3.3.4.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Confirm the wider benefits that will arise from meeting the needs of all customer groups and thereby define the Value for Money of the investment.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 61.2pt; text-indent:-25.2pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">3.3.5.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Identify </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">areas where investmen</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">t in other modes will better meet</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the needs of customers and identify the parties best able to deliver that investment</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">3.4.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The investment identified</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> should b</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> considered alongside the wider econ</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">omic</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> need</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> of the surrounding area. Action for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">R</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">oads proposes </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">route based studies as the basis for d</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">eveloping investment strategies. In order to be effective,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> these strategies need to work closely with LE</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">P</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">LTB</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s and local authorities to ensure all appropriate customer needs are addressed.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">3.5.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">I</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">n proposing the additional</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> analysis outlined above it should be recognised that the strategic road network is required to d</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">eliver in such a complex environment</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> there can never be a complete answer</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">I</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">t is important that benefits are delivered effectively</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> against a pipeline with a hi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">gh degree of certainty</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> rather than constant refinement of modelling that will never</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> be able to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> present a complete</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> or accurate</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> picture. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">3.6.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">CIHT suggest that the work proposed above should be carried out alongside existing appraisal of schemes in the short ter</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">m.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">3.7.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The role of the regulator identified in the response to question 1 in identifying the needs of customers is an important one t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">o be developed as the Highways Agency changes form.</span></p><h2 style="font-size:13pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:108%; margin:2pt 0pt 0pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid"><span style="color:#2e74b5; font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:13pt">&#xa0;</span></h2><h1 style="font-weight:normal; margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="color:#2e74b5; font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:16pt">4.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="color:#2e74b5; font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:16pt">How can we improve the reliability and efficiency of travel on the strateg</span><span style="color:#2e74b5; font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:16pt">ic road network? What impact will new technology have?</span></h1><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">4.1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Significant improvements to the reliability</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">efficiency</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and safety</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> of travel have already been m</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">de on the S</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">RN </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">by in</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">vestment utilising technology. T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">he increasing </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">length of the network utilising Manage</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">d </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">M</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">otorway techniques to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">increase capacity are welcome. T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">he technology available to vehicle users, both in terms of safety and i</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">nformation have developed and wi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ll continue t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">o</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> develop rapidly.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">4.2.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The reformed operator of the network needs to work closely with </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the vehicle development sector to maximise the benefit of investm</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ents both to vehicles and the network. Having c</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">larity </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">of custom