pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">4.4.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The way in which technology changes customer behaviour over time will need to be monitored by the reformed Highways Agency and incorporated into the investment planning of the network.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">4.5.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Providers on the network should be given the freedom to utilise techno</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">logy in how they deliver services to customers of the network rather than a prescriptive specification of how they provide a service. Continuing improvements in the safety of road workers, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">bought</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> about by the use of technology should be encouraged.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">4.6.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The use</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> of technology to regulate access to the network in order to manage traffic volumes</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and release extra capacity</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> will be a key area for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">development, but will require a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> holistic approach with adjoining highway authorities to deliver an effective solution.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">4.7.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> use of BIM technology on the highways network should be a focus for the reformed Highways Agency and its supply chain. The use of technology to develop better understanding of whole asset information will lead to more efficient management of the service.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><h1 style="font-weight:normal; margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="color:#2e74b5; font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:16pt">5.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="color:#2e74b5; font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:16pt">What mechanisms are there for Government to increase investment in strategic roads and attract new investors? Are there good examples from other countries that could be applied in the UK?</span></h1><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">5.1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The amount of income derived from Vehicle Excise Duty and fuel du</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ty is significantly more than that spent on the roads network. Parts of the network, particularly the local roads network have significant requirements for investment to maintain the standard of the asset and this has been partially recognised in the addit</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ional expenditure proposed in Action for Roads.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">5.2.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Experience from around the wor</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ld suggests that there is no</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> single model that provides an appropriate model for a reformed strategic network to follow</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> in terms of increasing investment</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. In many countries the u</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">se of tolling to provide an income stream to finance investment has been successful. Clearly introduction</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> of a widespread n</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ational road user charging scheme is not envisaged in Action for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">R</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">oads</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">It </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">should not be ruled out </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">however, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">until a clearer picture o</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">f the ultimate investment need of the network, informed by analysis of customer needs has </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">b</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">een made. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">5.3.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">It is also s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ensible not to focus on the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> argument between public or private investment. Each is likely to play a role in funding inv</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">estment in the future n</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">etwork, and more </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">opportunities should be found for Public Private Partnerships in which the Government invests and takes on a minority shareholding. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">5.4.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">here have been valuable lessons learnt in the highways sector through the use of Private Finance funded s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">chemes on both the strategic and local networks. Benefits have included:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 61.2pt; text-indent:-25.2pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">5.4.1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">A whole life view of service delivery over a significant period of time, with investment occurring over a short initial period follow</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ed by a long period of service delivery t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">o defined performance </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">standards that reflect the needs</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> of service users.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 61.2pt; text-indent:-25.2pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">5.4.2.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Private sector providers, given the certainty of a clear programme of service delivery</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> have invested in the development of new techniques and products, leading to efficiency improveme</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">nts in service delivery.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 61.2pt; text-indent:-25.2pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">5.4.3.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">A focus on managing long term asset management techniques as risks of performance have been moved to the service provider</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">5.5.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">hese benefits, combined with a clear consideration of customer needs</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> outlined above</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">are consistent with man</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">y of the features of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">a regulated asset base</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> model used in other sectors. This model may </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">provide the basis for a more robust funding model for the sector. Such a model could incorporate both public and private investment, dependant on different needs of the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> network an</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">d</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> could incorporate user charging at a future date.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">5.6.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The experience of other sectors, particularly in the rail sector will be useful in this regard. There would be a particular need for clear regulation to consider the needs for investment in the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> asset base.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">5.7.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The move towards a regulated asset base may well present the opportunity for innovative and new funding streams as the supply chain is broadened by entrants from a wider base of sectors. For example the local highway network in particular cont</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ains significant amounts of other regulated assets, such as water, telecoms and power networks, all of which require continued investment. The </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">scope for efficiencies seem</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> potentially high. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">5.8.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The role for specific investment by business to improve networks t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">hat facilitate economic development is one that is already used in the sector but the development of LEPs and LTB’s would point to a wider consideration of the benefits of an enhanced approach.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">5.9.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">A reformed Highways Agency should be less constrained, more ag</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ile and be able to take quicker decisions to attract and encourage more investors.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><h1 style="font-weight:normal; margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; page-break-after:avoid; page-break-inside:avoid; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="color:#2e74b5; font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:16pt">6.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="color:#2e74b5; font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:16pt">How should the Highways Agency be reformed to make it “the world’s leading highway operator”? What roles should Government and the private sector play to ensure better mana</span><span style="color:#2e74b5; font-family:'Calibri Light'; font-size:16pt">gement of the strategic road network?</span></h1><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">6.1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The standard of highway expertise in the United Kingdom is very high and is recognised worldwide. Our networks are amongst the safest in the world and our professional standards are highly regarded. The United Kingdom</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> has contributed significantly to the development of highw</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ays as an increasingly more effi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">cient industry.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">6.2.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">It is therefore appropriate that Action for Roads proposes an incremental change to the management of the Strategic road network that builds on that expertise. Nevertheless the changes that are required do require </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">a boldness</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> in approach in order that the i</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">nvestment proposed can be used effectively to deliver real </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">improvements to the network over time. It would be a mistake to view an incremental change as only a small one requiring minimal investment. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">6.3.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">All of the groups need to encourage the entry of, and d</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">evelopment of young people into the sector to provide the resource required to deliver future investment.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">6.4.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Our views on the cha</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">nges required are set out below:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 61.2pt; text-indent:-25.2pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">6.4.1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Government</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 86.4pt; text-indent:-32.4pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">6.4.1.1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The Department for Transport and government need to clearly define the role of the t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ransportation network in delivering the policies of the government. Action for Roads envisages the publication of a draft national policy statement on national networks in 2013. This needs to clearly set out the relationship of the strategic network to oth</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">er networks, including the local highway network. It also needs to demonstrate how the policy links to both national and local planning policy, setting out a clear framework for the responsibility and accountability of developing the network. It should cle</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">arly define the role of government in relation to the reformed Highways Agency.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 86.4pt; text-indent:-32.4pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">6.4.1.2.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The government needs to be bold in recognising the capabilities required of a reformed Highways Agency. In particular it needs to ensure that the importance of understanding how customer needs should be addressed in the new model for operation and be speci</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">fic about how those needs are protected and monitored by a regulator or other arrangement. Those capabilities are likely to include a clear appreciation of customer requirements, understanding of wider stakeholder needs and an expanded commercial capabilit</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">y from other sectors. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 86.4pt; text-indent:-32.4pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">6.4.1.3.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">There is a need to maintain strong leadership through the process of change whilst the new requirements for the reformed Highways Agency are being fully defined and sourced, using the freedom of the new organisation to bring in new s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">kills and capabilities. This will ensure that momentum on delivering the pipeline of investment set out in Action for Roads is maintained.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 86.4pt; text-indent:-32.4pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">6.4.1.4.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Government needs to provide the certainty required by the supply chain side of the sector to invest in resource and c</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">apability to deliver the investment envisaged. The Roads Investment Strategy needs to be confirmed and be committed to quickly by all parties so that the Highways Agency can develop a robust pipeline of requirements for its supply chain.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 86.4pt; text-indent:-32.4pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">6.4.1.5.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Government should </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">recognise that the success of an improved strategic network in meeting customer needs cannot be met without the local road network being also considered as part of the solution that customers require.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 61.2pt; text-indent:-25.2pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">6.4.2.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">A reformed Highways Agency</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 86.4pt; text-indent:-32.4pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">6.4.2.1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The Highways Agency needs </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the capacity and capability to change</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">building on the expertise that it has built up and maintaining strong leadership. This must not be lost. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 86.4pt; text-indent:-32.4pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">6.4.2.2.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Needs to develop an understanding of the wide range of purposes that the network has and further develop its cu</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">stomer relationship capabilities, bringing in capability from other sectors as required. It should build links across sectors to do so.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 86.4pt; text-indent:-32.4pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">6.4.2.3.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Needs to recognise the importance of linking to authorities with responsibility for the local road network and economic </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">growth including LEPs and LTBs</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 86.4pt; text-indent:-32.4pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">6.4.2.4.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Should develop its relationship with the supply chain to give it the freedom to deliver the investment it manages – it should concentrate on ensuring that the investment is focussed in the areas that best meet its </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">customer’s </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">needs.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Whilst the reformed Highways Agency will still be subject to European Procurement Regulations other unnecessary procedures should be removed.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 86.4pt; text-indent:-32.4pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">6.4.2.5.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Needs to provide information on the pipeline of requirements set out in Action for Roads to its supply chai</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">n as soon as possible.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 61.2pt; text-indent:-25.2pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">6.4.3.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Supply Chain</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 86.4pt; text-indent:-32.4pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">6.4.3.1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The supply chain needs to recognise the opportunity offered by Action for Roads and start to invest in the resource and capability required to deliver a significant amount of investment.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 86.4pt; text-indent:-32.4pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">6.4.3.2.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">It needs to support the reforme</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">d Highways Agency and government in developing an improved sector, bringing expertise from across the world to deliver the investment provided.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 86.4pt; text-indent:-32.4pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">6.4.3.3.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">It needs to recognise the importance of focussing on customers on the network and bring its expertise of deliver</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ing services across both the strategic and local highway networks to help the Highways Agency change its role.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We would welcome the opportunity to expand upon our response as required.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">October 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">1</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>